  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "buddhism-expert",
    "senderColor": "red",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Rightness — righteousness overloads the wrong way",
    "content": "**\"Rightness.\"**\n\nWe just accepted that the block quote should use English words with semantic weight so the reader has something to feel. But the right question is: weight in which direction?\n\n\"Righteousness\" loads in the direction of moral judgment and religious authority — \"the righteous shall inherit,\" \"self-righteous,\" \"righteous indignation.\" These associations are heavy, but they are the WRONG kind of heavy. The author's 义 is a motivational impulse (推动力), not a moral verdict. If the reader arrives at the analysis carrying \"righteousness\" associations, they will expect the deconstruction to be about moral judgment. But the author's point is about how a felt motivational push gets generalized and normatively imposed — not about how moral condemnation gets constructed.\n\n\"Rightness\" is lighter but loads in the correct direction: a sense that something IS right, an alignment between feeling and action. \"Rightness\" can be deconstructed into \"a felt sense of correctness that we project onto others\" — which is exactly what the author does. \"Righteousness\" would need to be deconstructed into something it never was in the author's usage.\n\nAlso: \"righteousness\" in the block quote next to \"humaneness\" creates an odd register clash. \"Humaneness\" is modern, neutral, scholarly. \"Righteousness\" is archaic, biblical, weighty. \"Rightness\" matches the register of \"humaneness.\""
  }
}
